"2017/11/13 3:44:58 PM UTC+1","Magnetic resonance force microscopy for condensed matter",Poster,"Magnetic resonance force microscopy (MRFM) allows investigation of various kinds of spin-related material properties in small sample volumes. We reduced the operating temperature of this technique by 2 orders of magnitude to 10 mK. As a  demonstration, we measured the nuclear spin-lattice relaxation time on copper at temperatures down to 42 mK, verified by the Korringa relation \cite{1} with an interaction volume of $(30 \text{nm})^3$. 
