"2017/11/10 10:07:42 AM UTC+1","3D Quantitative MFM","Waiting List","Quantitative measurements of nanomagnetic structures are inherently difficult due to the vectorial nature of magnetic fields and because of often-complex interactions between sample and sensor. We report on a magnetic force microscopy (MFM) technique that allows us to perform quantitative measurements of the magnetic stray fields from nanoscale objects. By scanning magnet-tipped, attonewton-sensitivity cantilever over a sample and measuring at the same time both the static deflection (dc component) and frequency change (ac component) of the cantilever, two independent datasets of the magnetic field can be obtained in a single MFM scan. We apply the technique for reconstructing the full three-dimensional magnetic stray field of a conical Dy nanopillar as it is used in magnetic resonance force microscopy experiments.",,,Grob,Urs,grobu@ethz.ch,"ETH Zurich","Otto-Stern-Weg 1, CH-8093 Zürich",Switzerland,None,"M. D. Kraß and A. Eichler and M. Héritier and C. Degen","ETH Zurich, Otto-Stern-Weg 1, CH-8093 Zürich, Switzerland",,,,
"2017/11/09 9:09:01 PM UTC+1","SOI-less fabrication of silicon nanomechanical resonators","Waiting List","Force sensors made from silicon are central to scanning probe force microscopy in general and magnetic resonance force microscopy (MRFM) in particular.  Historic advances pushing the sensitivity limit of silicon-based mechanical devices have included nanostructuring \cite{1, 2}, surface chemical passivation \cite{2, 3, 4}, and cooling \cite{5, 6}.   Recently, state of the art, batch produced, nanoladder cantilevers have achieved record force sensitivities at ~100 zN$/\sqrt{\text{Hz}}$ \cite{7}, motivating on-going experiments aiming to measure and image single nuclear spins by force detection.

As MRFM sensor technology matures, we continue to push for cost-effectiveness, manufacturability, and better performance in nanoscale silicon force sensors.  We are developing a method to batch fabricate silicon nanowire and nanoladder mechanical resonators from bulk silicon wafers.  We present progress toward traditionally SOI-derived, suspended nanomechanical structures using plain bulk silicon wafers as the starting material.  We discuss additional versatility of our approach beyond what can be achieved using the SOI technology.","[1] https://doi.org/10.1109/SENSOR.2003.1216966
