"2017/11/24 4:59:05 PM UTC+1","Spin detection using a nanotube mechanical resonator","Waiting List","Micro-scale mechanical resonators are highly sensitive force sensors, enabling the detection of very small ensembles of electron spins or even one single electron spin [1]. Recently, we showed that mechanical resonators made of suspended carbon nanotubes display outstanding properties, such as quality factors up to 5 million, and force noise as low as 10-21 N/Hz^(-1/2) [2]. We propose to use this excellent sensitivity capability to detect and manipulate the electron spins of molecules deposited on top of the carbon nanotubes. For this, we use the specific protocol developed by Nichol et al. [3] and a superconducting coplanar waveguide very close to the nanotube to generate both the oscillating magnetic field and the magnetic field gradient, which are needed to manipulate the electron spins of the molecules, and to detect them.","[1]https://www-nature-com.recursos.biblioteca.upc.edu/articles/nature02658
